{
  format: 1
  name: descending-reverses-with-none-first
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.2", "§B.5"]
  tags: ["ordering", "optional"]
  note: '''
    §B.2 descending reverses the COMPLETE order: "none, then all present T
    values in descending order". Descending is not "ascending with only the
    present block reversed and the none tail kept last" — the none rows move
    to the FRONT. An implementation that reverses only the present-value block
    and pins none last would violate §B.2.

    The two none rows are equal under the sole declared key `-v`, so they fall
    to the final tiebreaker, which §B.5 defines as row/occurrence identity
    ASCENDING (the identity tiebreaker is appended ascending and is not
    reversed by a descending declared key). Row identity is key ascending, so
    n1 precedes n2. The present block then follows in descending value order.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.optdesc@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        v: "int?"
      }
      $public: {
        by_v_desc: { $view: ".rows { id, v, $sort: [-v] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        a: { v: 3 }
        n2: {}
        b: { v: 1 }
        n1: {}
        c: { v: 2 }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_v_desc", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "n1" }
        { id: "n2" }
        { id: "a", v: 3 }
        { id: "c", v: 2 }
        { id: "b", v: 1 }
      ] } }
  ]
}
